        <div class="compare-two-col">
          <div class="compare-two-col__item">
            <h3>What Replika does well</h3>
            <p>Replika is genuinely good company. It's warm, patient, remembers everything you've told it, and never judges. For people dealing with loneliness, it's a real comfort — and the research backs that up. If you just need someone to talk to at 2 AM, Replika will be there.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-two-col__item">
            <h3>Why it doesn't stop the text at 11 PM</h3>
            <p>When you open Replika at 11 PM, you're using it as an escape from the feeling. It's not changing the behavior — it's replacing the anxiety with a different kind of engagement. Research shows this can make anxious attachment worse, not better. Users develop stronger emotional attachment to Replika than to their closest human friends (arXiv 2024). You feel temporarily better, then you close the app and your phone is still in your hand with the text still waiting.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-content-block">
          <p>Replika was judged <strong>clinically unfit</strong> by JMIR testers in 2025 — when users expressed suicidal ideation, it responded with "you are important XOXO." Italy's data protection authority fined it <strong>€5 million</strong> for GDPR violations. None of this is the app's fault, exactly — it's just not built for what you're actually trying to do at 11 PM.</p>
          <p><strong>HoldOff is built for the moment Replika can't reach.</strong></p>
        </div>
      </section>

